he population. ","hasAlt":true,"isDecorative":false,"isMissingAlt":false,"ariaHidden":false,"rolePresentation":false,"renderedWidth":623,"renderedHeight":400,"naturalWidth":623,"naturalHeight":400,"loading":null,"decoding":null,"altVerdict":"TOO_LONG","altReason":"alt text is 486 characters — consider a caption or description","bytes":46553},{"src":"https://www.cdc.gov/TemplatePackage/images/icon_out.png","alt":"External Web Site Icon","hasAlt":true,"isDecorative":false,"isMissingAlt":false,"ariaHidden":false,"rolePresentation":false,"renderedWidth":10,"renderedHeight":10,"naturalWidth":10,"naturalHeight":10,"loading":null,"decoding":null,"altVerdict":"GOOD","altReason":"present, no red flags","bytes":232},{"src":"https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/figures/m5916a3f3.gif","alt":"The figure shows the percentage of current smokers among adults, 1994-2008, and high school students, 2001-2007, in New York City. The decline in adult smoking prevalence since 2002 is greater than that in the United States overall and represents 350,000 fewer smokers in New York City.","hasAlt":true,"isDecorative":false,"isMissingAlt":false,"ariaHidden":false,"rolePresentation":false,"renderedWidth":640,"renderedHeight":284,"naturalWidth":640,"naturalHeight":284,"loading":null,"decoding":null,"altVerdict":"TOO_LONG","altReason":"alt text is 286 characters — consider a caption or description","bytes":15962},{"src":"https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/figures/m5916a3f4.gif","alt":"The figure shows the comparison of carcinogenic nitrosamine content of Marlboro and local brand cigarettes in eight countries, from 2000-2001. The design of a tobacco product substantially influences the levels of toxic chemicals it emits, as seen through the differences in levels of tobacco-specific nitrosamines that result from the use of different types of cigarettes in different countries. Except for the United States, local brands in those countries contained considerably less nitrosamine compared w